Where?

44
00:04:08,694 --> 00:04:10,844
No, I'll tell Walter and Peter.

45
00:04:17,168 --> 00:04:20,009
So. We're gonna have
to take a rain check.

46
00:04:21,543 --> 00:04:24,597
That's okay, Aunt Liv.
I know you have an important job.

47
00:04:31,609 --> 00:04:34,982
I'm gonna call the Jacobsens
and see if they can babysit.

48
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:37,259
And then I'll...

49
00:04:37,384 --> 00:04:38,694
Make pancakes?

50
00:04:39,349 --> 00:04:41,199
And I'll make you pancakes.

51
00:04:44,201 --> 00:04:45,901
Are you sure it was him?

52
00:04:46,161 --> 00:04:49,291
We don't have the security footage
yet, but an eyewitness said

53
00:04:49,416 --> 00:04:51,633
that he was wearing
a gray suit and a hat,

54
00:04:51,758 --> 00:04:54,558
quote, "One of those old ones
from the '60s."

55
00:04:55,110 --> 00:04:57,760
We don't have
any information on the girl?

56
00:04:57,967 --> 00:05:01,467
The police showed her picture around
the museum but no one knew who she was.

57
00:05:02,165 --> 00:05:03,465
Is Walter awake?

58
00:05:05,163 --> 00:05:06,163
He's in...

59
00:05:07,491 --> 00:05:08,591
the kitchen.

60
00:05:09,309 --> 00:05:11,769
- Talking to him's not gonna be easy.
- Why?

61
00:05:13,417 --> 00:05:14,717
We have company.

62
00:05:21,517 --> 00:05:25,157
I need you to tell me what you know
about the man we call "the Observer."

63
00:05:26,308 --> 00:05:28,176
You once referred to him
as your friend.

64
00:05:28,301 --> 00:05:30,537
And it seems that he may
have kidnapped a woman.

65
00:05:31,305 --> 00:05:33,755
They call it
"the Strawberry Supreme."

66
00:05:34,467 --> 00:05:36,543
His favorite ice cream store
is shut down.

67
00:05:36,711 --> 00:05:38,906
He made me wait in line with him
for four hours yesterday

68
00:05:39,031 --> 00:05:40,742
just so he could have
one last milkshake.

69
00:05:40,867 --> 00:05:42,631
They have a secret ingredient.
It's...

70
00:05:42,756 --> 00:05:45,346
It's mundane but it's...
Oh, it's sublime.

71
00:05:45,471 --> 00:05:47,119
And I am trying to stimulate

72
00:05:47,244 --> 00:05:48,959
my olfactory and...

73
00:05:49,257 --> 00:05:51,891
gustatory senses
to try to recreate it.

74
00:05:52,016 --> 00:05:53,811
Walter?
Can you come with me?

75
00:05:56,565 --> 00:05:59,706
We've recorded him at over
three dozen fringe events.

76
00:06:00,397 --> 00:06:01,705
Do you remember him?

77
00:06:02,304 --> 00:06:03,112
Of course.

78
00:06:04,730 --> 00:06:07,203
But there's nothing more
than I've told you before.

79
00:06:08,928 --> 00:06:10,712
Peter and I were in a car crash.

80
00:06:10,837 --> 00:06:12,755
In a frozen lake, when I was a boy.

81
00:06:13,739 --> 00:06:15,058
We were drowning, and...

82
00:06:16,440 --> 00:06:18,066
he dove in and saved us.

83
00:06:21,320 --> 00:06:23,132
But you say he's kidnapped a woman?

84
00:06:23,386 --> 00:06:24,758
We think he may have.

85
00:06:24,926 --> 00:06:26,802
Why?
What are you thinking, Walter?

86
00:06:28,408 --> 00:06:29,455
Hey, guys?

87
00:06:29,580 --> 00:06:32,052
The footage from the abduction
has been downloaded.

88
00:06:32,177 --> 00:06:35,962
Also, the police found a book
on a bench by the museum

89
00:06:36,087 --> 00:06:37,995
that had some kind of
weird writing in it.

90
00:06:38,120 --> 00:06:39,410
And they think it was his?

91
00:06:39,535 --> 00:06:42,393
Well, they don't know,
but Agent Broyles is sending it over.

92
00:06:43,567 --> 00:06:45,925
- Have we I.D.'ed the victim?
- No, not yet.

93
00:06:47,223 --> 00:06:48,453
Wait a minute, Astrid.

94
00:06:50,989 --> 00:06:52,295
Can you zoom in?

95
00:06:54,664 --> 00:06:55,837
Now freeze it.

96
00:06:57,754 --> 00:06:58,917
Peter, that isn't him.

97
00:07:01,578 --> 00:07:02,948
That's a different guy.

98
00:07:05,619 --> 00:07:07,298
There's more than one observer.

99
00:07:11,938 --> 00:07:14,266
Stop. Ho... hold on.
What just happened right there?

100
00:07:22,776 --> 00:07:23,728
Was he hit?

101
00:07:33,888 --> 00:07:35,610
Who are these people?

102
00:07:59,084 --> 00:08:00,729
"Please don't hurt me."

103
00:08:01,892 --> 00:08:03,565
"Why are you doing this?"

104
00:08:04,190 --> 00:08:05,567
"Please let me go."

105
00:08:06,407 --> 00:08:08,298
"I promise I won't tell anyone."

106
00:08:08,423 --> 00:08:10,364
"You don't have to do this to me."

107
00:08:21,584 --> 00:08:22,415
"Please."

108
00:08:26,212 --> 00:08:27,612
It will be safer...

109
00:08:28,145 --> 00:08:29,341
if you stay quiet.

110
00:08:40,807 --> 00:08:42,569
Her name's Christine Hollis.

111
00:08:43,373 --> 00:08:46,569
27 years old in the masters program
for Fine Arts at B.U.

112
00:08:47,420 --> 00:08:49,308
As far as we can tell,
she's no one special.

113
00:08:49,433 --> 00:08:52,016
Her parents are deceased.
No siblings, no arrest record.

114
00:08:52,141 --> 00:08:53,974
$2,700 in her bank account.

115
00:08:54,503 --> 00:08:55,950
Nothing unusual about her at all.

116
00:08:56,075 --> 00:08:58,453
- Well, do we have a home address?
- We're working on it now.

117
00:08:59,270 --> 00:09:00,958
Assuming she's still alive.

118
00:09:01,138 --> 00:09:03,156
We have no reason yet
to think otherwise.

119
00:09:03,873 --> 00:09:05,481
Well, that's just it, isn't it?

120
00:09:05,811 --> 00:09:07,504
I mean, we don't know what to think.

121
00:09:08,444 --> 00:09:09,812
I... I'm lost.

122
00:09:10,868 --> 00:09:13,663
24 years ago, one of them
saved Walter and Peter.

123
00:09:13,858 --> 00:09:15,973
Walter doesn't know why,
or he can't remember.

124
00:09:16,098 --> 00:09:18,919
But beyond that,
everything we know about these guys,

125
00:09:19,044 --> 00:09:21,777
the little that there is
suggests that they just watch.

126
00:09:21,902 --> 00:09:23,900
They don't get involved.
But now...

127
00:09:26,082 --> 00:09:28,383
Figure out why he took this girl.

128
00:09:28,610 --> 00:09:30,324
What makes her the exception.

129
00:09:33,526 --> 00:09:35,493
Do that, and I think
you'll find him.

130
00:09:38,076 --> 00:09:40,442
Hey, I think we may
have a lead on the Observer.

131
00:09:41,393 --> 00:09:43,595
Walter. Look at this.
In his book.

132
00:09:44,751 --> 00:09:46,460
I think that might be blood.

133
00:09:47,543 --> 00:09:48,925
You might be right, son.

134
00:09:50,037 --> 00:09:51,215
The scalpel, please.

135
00:09:52,431 --> 00:09:54,176
Did he ever tell you
why he saved us?

136
00:09:57,013 --> 00:09:58,055
The Observer.

137
00:10:03,377 --> 00:10:04,851
We're close, Walter.

138
00:10:05,676 --> 00:10:08,928
Whatever's going on, whatever
William Bell was warning Olivia about,

139
00:10:09,053 --> 00:10:11,990
these people have the answers,
I know it. I can feel it.

140
00:10:12,183 --> 00:10:14,207
This does not make any sense.

141
00:10:14,506 --> 00:10:15,372
What?

142
00:10:15,922 --> 00:10:17,215
His handwriting.

143
00:10:17,679 --> 00:10:21,622
<i>So far, I have counted</i>
<i>1,246 distinct characters</i>

144
00:10:21,747 --> 00:10:23,994
<i>and not a single one</i>
<i>of them repeats.</i>

145
00:10:24,119 --> 00:10:24,989
All right.

146
00:10:25,114 --> 00:10:26,792
Not all of us majored
in linguistics.

147
00:10:27,403 --> 00:10:30,170
It means that every written language
is based on repetition.

148
00:10:30,738 --> 00:10:33,632
So without repeated symbols,
language is not possible.

149
00:10:34,176 --> 00:10:35,605
Well, maybe it's a code.

150
00:10:36,097 --> 00:10:37,122
<i>Maybe.</i>

151
00:10:37,343 --> 00:10:39,575
<i>But if so, it is the most</i>
<i>complicated code</i>

152
00:10:39,700 --> 00:10:40,765
<i>I have ever seen.</i>

153
00:10:40,890 --> 00:10:43,039
<i>The computer can't make</i>
<i>any sense of this either.</i>

154
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:44,786
Hey, what you got?

155
00:10:45,108 --> 00:10:48,480
Nothing concrete on the symbols yet.
But we found a blood sample in the book.

156
00:10:48,648 --> 00:10:51,255
- The kidnapper's blood?
- <i>Not sure. Walter's analyzing it now.</i>

157
00:10:53,371 --> 00:10:54,347
Well,...

158
00:10:54,693 --> 00:10:57,162
we can't be certain
till we run the labs,

159
00:10:57,356 --> 00:11:01,148
but I've noticed the blood
has an orange tint,

160
00:11:01,636 --> 00:11:03,453
perhaps a sign of hemophilia.

161
00:11:03,621 --> 00:11:05,439
Well, if it is his blood

162
00:11:05,564 --> 00:11:08,345
and if he's a hemophiliac, then maybe
he was treated in a hospital,

163
00:11:08,470 --> 00:11:09,978
so there could be a record.

164
00:11:10,103 --> 00:11:13,046
I'll call Broyles. Have him put together
a list of all hemophiliacs in the area.

165
00:11:13,214 --> 00:11:14,773
Guys, I think I found something.

166
00:11:15,273 --> 00:11:18,391
It looks like someone else has been
investigating these symbols too.

167
00:11:19,032 --> 00:11:20,012
What?

168
00:11:20,952 --> 00:11:21,954
Who is it?

169
00:11:26,449 --> 00:11:29,359
Yeah, these things have been
blowing my mind for a while now.

170
00:11:29,484 --> 00:11:32,201
Do you see the little
half-circle with wings?

171
00:11:32,326 --> 00:11:34,291
That appears on a cuneiform tablet

172
00:11:34,416 --> 00:11:36,111
at the Iraqi National Museum.

173
00:11:36,236 --> 00:11:38,782
It's one of mankind's
earliest attempts at writing.

174
00:11:38,907 --> 00:11:41,908
And, uh, do you see this little
triangular curlycue thingie?

175
00:11:42,076 --> 00:11:44,036
That's etched on
the Iron Pillar of Delhi.

176
00:11:44,336 --> 00:11:46,453
900, B.C.
It's pretty weird, right?

177
00:11:46,578 --> 00:11:48,964
So Nina Sharp says you're FBI too.

178
00:11:49,089 --> 00:11:51,376
Uh... you don't look FBI.

179
00:11:52,378 --> 00:11:55,132
So you have no idea
what any of them mean.

180
00:11:55,798 --> 00:11:57,666
- What the symbols mean?
- Yeah.

181
00:11:58,124 --> 00:11:59,494
No, I have no idea.

182
00:12:00,691 --> 00:12:02,345
But I found something else.

183
00:12:04,049 --> 00:12:06,269
We all remember Paul Revere's ride,

184
00:12:06,394 --> 00:12:09,328
"one if by land, two if by sea,"
but before that,

185
00:12:09,453 --> 00:12:13,440
he was famous for his engraving
of the Boston Massacre.

186
00:12:14,176 --> 00:12:15,827
1770.

187
00:12:21,874 --> 00:12:22,991
Oh, come on.

188
00:12:23,262 --> 00:12:24,813
Well, that could be anybody.

189
00:12:28,023 --> 00:12:29,373
Marie Antoinette.

190
00:12:31,134 --> 00:12:32,720
1793.

191
00:12:39,384 --> 00:12:41,218
Sarajevo, 1914.

192
00:12:41,386 --> 00:12:44,993
Minutes before Archduke
Franz Ferdinand was shot,

193
00:12:45,557 --> 00:12:47,224
kicking off World War I.

194
00:12:47,490 --> 00:12:49,369
So they have been around forever.

195
00:12:49,494 --> 00:12:51,533
Or else, they're not limited

196
00:12:51,658 --> 00:12:54,179
by our human perception of time.

197
00:12:56,401 --> 00:12:57,564
Are you with me?

198
00:12:59,146 --> 00:13:01,173
We think of time as linear, right?

199
00:13:01,298 --> 00:13:04,703
Life is a journey.
You're born, and then you die.

200
00:13:04,893 --> 00:13:07,713
And to get from one end
to the other,

201
00:13:08,942 --> 00:13:11,466
there's only one way through.

202
00:13:14,109 --> 00:13:15,360
Unless...

203
00:13:15,656 --> 00:13:17,456
you look at it like this...

204
00:13:20,032 --> 00:13:21,315
and then...

205
00:13:22,507 --> 00:13:25,082
you can see at any point.

206
00:13:26,726 --> 00:13:28,299
It's all happening at once.

207
00:13:31,023 --> 00:13:32,918
So they're traveling through time.

208
00:13:34,083 --> 00:13:36,595
It's more like
they're observing time.

209
00:13:37,518 --> 00:13:38,817
I think...

210
00:13:39,571 --> 00:13:40,652
these guys...

211
00:13:40,820 --> 00:13:43,600
show up at important moments.

212
00:13:44,014 --> 00:13:47,778
Um, historical,
technological, scientific.

213
00:13:48,513 --> 00:13:49,536
But it's rare.

214
00:13:50,248 --> 00:13:52,414
Maybe two dozen different

215
00:13:53,280 --> 00:13:56,619
definite occurrences
in the past 5,000 years

216
00:13:56,744 --> 00:13:58,332
of human history.

217
00:13:58,499 --> 00:14:01,817
But recently,
I've charted 26 sightings

218
00:14:01,942 --> 00:14:04,468
in the past three months alone.

219
00:14:05,268 --> 00:14:06,720
It kind of makes you wonder.

220
00:14:07,159 --> 00:14:08,055
Why now?

221
00:14:09,016 --> 00:14:10,735
And what's about to happen.

222
00:14:12,724 --> 00:14:14,173
More hot sauce, gentlemen?

223
00:14:17,178 --> 00:14:19,045
- Thank you.
- Sure thing.

224
00:14:34,523 --> 00:14:36,166
We have a situation with August.

225
00:14:47,501 --> 00:14:49,496
- Who is she?
- I don't know.

226
00:14:49,969 --> 00:14:52,766
But she's supposed to be on
Tropos Air, Flight 821.

227
00:14:58,409 --> 00:14:59,898
Why did he abduct her?

228
00:15:00,838 --> 00:15:01,962
We don't know.

229
00:15:02,570 --> 00:15:04,865
And the flight has
already left the terminal.

230
00:15:05,240 --> 00:15:07,572
Then he's created an irregularity.

231
00:15:07,983 --> 00:15:09,513
We'll need to repair it.

232
00:15:11,070 --> 00:15:12,469
Contact Donald.

233
00:15:58,522 --> 00:16:00,000
I just don't understand it.

234
00:16:00,582 --> 00:16:02,487
Why would anyone want
to kidnap Christine?

235
00:16:02,612 --> 00:16:04,651
Well, that's what we're trying
to figure out.

236
00:16:04,776 --> 00:16:07,911
- So you two aren't roommates.
- No. We're friends.

237
00:16:08,036 --> 00:16:10,458
Taking a bunch of sculpture
classes together.

238
00:16:10,670 --> 00:16:12,846
I'm subletting her room
while she's away.

239
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:14,707
Was supposed to be away.

240
00:16:15,183 --> 00:16:17,405
- Where was she supposed to be?
- Italy.

241
00:16:18,104 --> 00:16:19,728
She was supposed to fly today.

242
00:16:20,395 --> 00:16:23,815
She was gonna spend the semester
studying ceramics in Rome.

243
00:16:24,072 --> 00:16:26,318
Well, do you have a copy
of her itinerary?

244
00:16:26,610 --> 00:16:29,648
Her flight to Rome, or... maybe
where she was gonna be staying?

245
00:16:29,864 --> 00:16:32,244
She emailed me one.
I can print out a copy for you.

246
00:16:32,789 --> 00:16:34,100
Is this Christine?

247
00:16:35,335 --> 00:16:38,042
It's a terrible story, actually.

248
00:16:38,167 --> 00:16:40,832
Her family was visiting
relatives in San Francisco.

249
00:16:41,238 --> 00:16:43,046
A few hours after
that photo was taken,

250
00:16:43,171 --> 00:16:44,581
there was a big earthquake.

251
00:16:44,706 --> 00:16:45,789
The one in '89?

252
00:16:46,441 --> 00:16:48,673
They were driving on that bridge
when it happened,

253
00:16:49,309 --> 00:16:50,717
when it collapsed.

254
00:16:51,113 --> 00:16:52,769
Her parents were both killed.

